                <p>This is a main element. Like the immortals in <em>Highlander</em>, there should be only one of them. They support semantic classes, like <code>info</code>.</p>
            </main>
        </section>

        <section id="asides">
            <h2>Asides</h2>
            <p>Asides center everything inside them using flexbox. On mobile, they stack up their contents.</p>
            <aside>This is an aside.</aside>
            <p>It's useful for buttons:</p>
            <aside><button class="reaction">I'm centered!</button><button class="failure">Me too</button></aside>
        </section>

        <section id="section_example" class="reaction">
            <h2>Sections</h2>
            <p>Use of the <code>&lt;section&gt;</code> element (seen throughout this page) is encouraged. Sections have default CSS for spacing out your content that's aimed at getting it looking good on the first pass.</p>
            <p>Sections support semantic classes. This one is using <code>reaction</code>.</p>
        </section>

        <section id="typography">
            <h2>Typography</h2>

            <p>Typography rules are applied directly to HTML elements.</p>

            <h3>Headlines</h3>
            <p>Pretty much what you'd expect. Headlines are centered by default but that's easy to change.</p>

            <h1>This is headline text. (h1)</h1>
            <h2>This is headline text. (h2)</h2>
            <h3>This is headline text. (h3)</h3>
            <h4>This is headline text. (h4)</h4>
            <h5>This is headline text. (h5)</h5>
            <h6>This is headline text. (h6)</h6>

            <h3>Blockquotes</h3>
            <p>Blockquotes look like this:</p>
            <blockquote>
                You may delay, but time will not.
                <cite>Benjamin Franklin</cite>
            </blockquote>
            <p>They alternate switching sides by default, no classes needed.</p>
            <blockquote>
                Blushing is the color of virtue.
                <cite>Diogenes</cite>
            </blockquote>
            <p>They don't support semantic classes.</p>

            <h3>Paragraphs, etc.</h3>
            <p>Paragraphs (like this one!) are by default limited to 55 characters width (or whatever <code>@text-measure</code> is set to). They have an aggressive, but not too aggressive, line height of 1.62 (also a variable!). Like buttons and tables, paragraphs support all the semantic classes.</p>
            <p class="info">I'm informing you of something.</p>
            <p class="success">Your stuff wasn't lost in cyber space!</p>
            <p class="failure">I've made a huge mistake.</p>

            <h3>Other Block Elements</h3>
            <article>
                <pre>This is pre-formatted text</pre>
                <p>Horizontal rule:</p>
                <hr>
            </article>

            <h3>Other Inline Elements</h3>
            <p>Paragraphs may also contain <abbr title="abbreviations, to the layperson">abbreves</abbr> and <acronym title="Aribitrarily Invented Acronyms For Display Purposes">AIAFDPS</acronym>.</p>
            <p>Sometimes you just need an <code>an inline code snippet</code>.</p>

        </section>

        <section id="buttons">
            <h2>Buttons</h2>
            <p>Buttons are just <code>button</code> elements with a class corresponding to a semantic color name. There are six semantic colors by default, shown in these buttons here:</p>
            <aside>
                <button type="button" class="action">Action</button>
                <button type="button" class="reaction">Reaction</button>
            </aside>
            <aside>
                <button type="button" class="success">Success</button>
                <button type="button" class="failure">Failure</button>
            </aside>
            <aside>
                <button type="button" class="info">Info</button>
                <button type="button" class="warning">Warning</button>
            </aside>
            <p>Semantic colors respond to the color scheme too, so <code>@success</code> will always be the <em>right</em> green (along with its corresponding button). They don't have any other classes to worry about, until you add them, but they do respond well to font size changes:</p>
            <aside >
                <button type="button" class="info" style="font-size:22px;">22 pixels big</button>
                <button type="button" class="failure" style="font-size:1.5em;">1.5em of failure</button>
            </aside>
            <aside>
                <button type="button" class="action" style="font-size:12px;">12px action button</button>
                <button type="button" class="warning" style="font-size:7px;">Warning, this is too small</button>
            </aside>
        </section>

